<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-164-656  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 164 656.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  March 15 1989 n1452 p26(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The end of the line for the digital dinosaurs? (large digitalpublic telephone switches)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wilson, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Infrastructure of telecommunications in Europe is expected tochange significantly between the years 1989 and 2000 with theliberalization of the market and the increased use of fiber opticand digital switching technologies.andP;  Optical fiber's transmissionqualities will increase the spacing between subscriber andexchange, which will decrease cost and the number of exchanges.andO;Optical fiber also offers increased information-carrying capacity,which according to STC Telecommunications Ltd's Stuart Bailey,will cause an upheaval in the public switched telephone network.andO;This technology is the basis of British Telecommunication PLC'snew flexible access system (FAS).andP;  FAS, which is being developedby STC, combines the high capacity of the broadband optical fiberwith the latest digital switching and multiplexing technology.andO;The system's goal is to reduce dependence on large switchingstructures.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   STC Telecommunications Ltd. (communication systems)British Telecommunications PLC (communication systems).andO;Topic:     TelecommunicationsFiber OpticsDigital CommunicationsEuropeNetworks.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographchart.andO;Caption:   Blueprint for the digital switch infrastructure of the future.andO;(chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>